"*F*Solid;Horizontal1;;White;Gray;100*/F**S*DarkGray;Solid;1*/S**T*Black;Microsoft Sans Serif, 10pt;MiddleCenter;*/T*" "The RS-25 or also known as the Space Shuttle Main Engine (SSME) is a closed loop, fuel rich engine. It uses liquid fuel (hydrogen) and a liquid oxidiser (oxygen) in a cryogenic state. Developed by Rocketdyne (now Pratt & Whitney Rocketdyne and Areojet Rocketdyne), it was used in NASA's Space Shuttle. NASA is planning to use this rocket engine with the Space Launch System (SLS), successor of the Space Shuttle. " "{COMPONENT}Text Box - 2" "True" "Wrap" "" "Text Box - 2" "10" "10" "*F*Solid;Horizontal1;;Transparent;Gray;100*/F**S*Transparent;Solid;1*/S**T*Black;Microsoft Sans Serif, 12pt;TopLeft;*/T*" "" "" "0" "0" "0"

"*F*Solid;Horizontal1;;White;Gray;100*/F**S*DarkGray;Solid;1*/S**T*Black;Microsoft Sans Serif, 10pt;MiddleCenter;*/T*" "The RS-25 has a staged combustion cycle due to the inclusion of the pre-burners. It uses a mixture of gaseous hydrogen and liquid oxygen in the combustion process. In the pre-burners, most of the fuel and a small amount of oxygen are preburned in a very fuel-rich mixture. The hot gas from the pre-burner combustion process is then used to drive the turbopumps and then directed to the main combustion chamber. As this hot gas is very fuel-rich, there are significant amounts of hydrogen that can still react with an oxidiser. Liquid oxygen is then injected into the main combustion chamber where the oxygen to fuel ratio is roughly 6."
